Location within [Shropshire](/Shropshire)

Ludford is a small village and civil parish in south [Shropshire](/Shropshire), England. The parish lies immediately adjacent to the [market town](/Market_town) of [Ludlow](/Ludlow) and, historically, formed part of [Herefordshire](/Herefordshire) until the late‑nineteenth century realignment of county boundaries. Situated on the south bank of the [River Teme](/River_Teme), Ludford is linked to Ludlow by the ancient [Ludford Bridge](/Ludford_Bridge), a grade‑I listed structure that carries the B4361 road across the water. The village’s topography is characterised by low‑lying flood‑plain topography to the north and the rising limestone uplands to the south, giving it a distinct geological profile that includes the fossil‑rich [Ludford Corner](/Ludford_Corner) exposure.  

Population 673&#160;(civil parish, 2011) &#91;1&#93; [OS&#160;grid&#160;reference](/Ordnance_Survey_National_Grid) SO511739 •&#160;[London](/London) 154 miles (248&#160;km) [Civil parish](/Civil_parish)

The 2011 census recorded a total of 673 residents within the civil parish of Ludford. This figure reflects a modest increase from the 395 persons counted in 2001, a growth largely attributed to new housing developments on the eastern fringe of Ludlow that have spilled over the parish boundary. The built‑up area of the village itself, however, remains small, with fewer than 150 inhabitants recorded in the same period; the remainder of the parish population is dispersed across the surrounding hamlets and rural settlements.  

[Unitary&#160;authority](/Districts_of_England) [Shropshire](/Shropshire_Council)

Administratively, Ludford falls under the unitary authority of [Shropshire](/Shropshire), which was established in 2009 to replace the previous two‑tier system of county and district councils. The unitary authority is responsible for a wide range of local services, including education, social care, and strategic planning, and it operates under the oversight of the [Shropshire](/Shropshire) County Council.  

[Ceremonial&#160;county](/Ceremonial_counties_of_England) [Shropshire](/Shropshire)

Ceremonially, Ludford is part of the ceremonial county of [Shropshire](/Shropshire), one of England’s historic counties that retains symbolic roles in ceremonial functions such as the appointment of a Lord Lieutenant. The ceremonial county boundaries largely correspond to the historic boundaries of Shropshire, though they have been adjusted over time to reflect changes in local government.  

[Region](/Regions_of_England) [West Midlands](/West_Midlands_(region))

Geographically, Ludford is located within the [West Midlands](/West_Midlands_(region)) region of England, a metropolitan region that includes the cities of Birmingham and Wolverhampton. The region is known for its diverse economy, ranging from advanced manufacturing to service industries, and it provides a strategic framework for regional development and transport planning.  

