Ludford is a small village and [civil parish](/Civil_parishes_in_England) in south [Shropshire](/Shropshire), England. The parish is situated adjacent to the [market town](/Market_town) of [Ludlow](/Ludlow) and was, until 1895, partly in [Herefordshire](/Herefordshire).  

The village lies on the south bank of the [River Teme](/River_Teme), with Ludlow occupying the northern bank, and it is connected to the town by the grade‑I listed [Ludford Bridge](/Ludford_Bridge). Geologically, Ludford is notable for the [Ludford Corner](/Ludford_Corner) fossil exposure, a site of international scientific importance.  

History and geography  

Etymology  

The place‑name “Ludford” derives from the [ford](/Ford_(crossing)) at the “loud waters” (the [River Teme](/River_Teme)), while the neighbouring town of Ludlow gets its name from the “low” (hill) beside those same waters. This linguistic heritage reflects the importance of the river as a natural landmark in the region.  

Domesday Book  

Ludford, along with Steventon and [the Sheet](/The_Sheet), appears in the [Domesday Book](/Domesday_Book) of 1086 as manors held by various Norman tenants. These settlements pre‑date the growth of Ludlow itself, which expanded during and after the construction of the [Norman castle there](/Ludlow_Castle).  

Shropshire and Herefordshire  

Historically, the parish straddled the boundary between Shropshire and [Herefordshire](/Herefordshire). The River Teme served as the county line, placing the village itself within Herefordshire, while the hamlets of Steventon and the Sheet fell within Shropshire. The [Local Government Act 1894](/Local_Government_Act_1894) transferred the Herefordshire portion of Ludford to Shropshire, moving it from the [Wolphy hundred](/Wolphy_hundred) to the [Munslow](/Munslow_(hundred)) hundred. This act also introduced elected [parish councils](/Parish_councils_in_England) for the first time.  

Hundreds  

In the Domesday era, Ludford was part of the Herefordshire hundred of Wolphy, whereas Steventon and the Sheet lay in the Shropshire hundred of Culvestan, a medieval division that persisted until the dissolution of hundreds in the 12th‑13th centuries. After the 1894 reforms, the former Culvestan area became part of the Munslow hundred, while the Wolphy hundred continued only as a historical reference.  

Rout of Ludford Bridge  

During the [Wars of the Roses](/Wars_of_the_Roses), a skirmish known as the [Rout of Ludford Bridge](/Rout_of_Ludford_Bridge) took place in 1459 near the bridge, marking a minor but symbolically significant engagement between royalist and Yorkist forces.  

Ludford House  

The village contains the former [country house](/English_country_house) known as Ludford House, originally a manor house that passed to the Charlton family in 1607. [Sir Job Charlton](/Sir_Job_Charlton,_1st_Baronet), a [speaker of the House of Commons](/Speaker_of_the_House_of_Commons_(United_Kingdom)), was created a baronet in 1686; the subsequent [Charlton baronetcy](/Charlton_baronets) later became extinct. By the 1840s the surrounding parkland had been enclosed and converted to farmland, and today Ludford House is divided into several private dwellings.  

Roads  

The historic [turnpike road](/Toll_road) to [Hereford](/Hereford) now forms part of the B4361, locally named the [Overton](/Overton,_Shropshire) Road within Ludford. Constructed in the 1820s, it traverses the former parkland of Ludford House. [Park Road](/Park_Road), once the main thoroughfare linking the ford and bridge to the south, was superseded in 1836 by routes through [Worcester](/Worcester,_England); it now serves local access only. [Whitcliffe Road](/Whitcliffe_Road) begins at the B4361, crosses Whitcliffe Common, and leads toward [Mortimer Forest](/Mortimer_Forest) before reaching [Wigmore](/Wigmore,_Herefordshire).  

[National Cycle Route 44](/National_Cycle_Route_44) runs through the area, providing a traffic‑free cycling corridor that bypasses the more congested B4361.  

Civil parish  

The civil parish of Ludford, which now extends beyond the historic village boundaries, encompasses the settlements of Ludford, the Sheet, Foldgate, Rocks Green, and Steventon. The parish is bisected by the [River Teme](/River_Teme), creating two distinct halves that are not directly connected by a bridge within the parish itself; crossing requires using a road bridge in Ludlow or a nearby footbridge. The [parish council](/Parish_councils_in_England) meets in the town of Ludlow, reflecting the practical cooperation between the two settlements.  

The view north across the Teme from the eastern part of Ludford village, with the skyline of Ludlow dominated by [St Laurence's Church](/St_Laurence%27s_Church,_Ludlow).

St Giles’ Church, a grade‑II* listed [Anglican parish church](/Anglican_parish_church) dedicated to [Saint Giles](/Saint_Giles), stands at the centre of the village. Its origins date to the 11th century, and it originally functioned as a chapel of [Bromfield Priory](/Bromfield_Priory).  

Public houses  

The historic [public house](/Public_house) known as the [Charlton Arms](/Charlton_Arms) stands by Ludford Bridge and has been converted into a restaurant and hotel. Originally called the Red Lion, it was renamed in honour of the [Charlton baronets](/Charlton_baronets), whose seat was Ludford House. Another former coaching inn, the Bell Inn on Park Road, was replaced by a private dwelling but retains historical significance.  

Geographic information  

The centre of Ludford sits at an elevation of 85.6 metres (281 ft) above sea level, giving the village a modest rise above the surrounding floodplain.  

